            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Bike size FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3 text-sm" id="faq">
                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-3 py-2 font-medium flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span>How accurate is this bike size calculator?</span>
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-xs">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 hidden faq-answer">
                    It uses industry‑standard formulas and ranges similar to
                    what many major brands publish. For most riders it will
                    narrow you down to one or two sizes that are very likely to
                    work. Final adjustments (stem length, saddle position, bar
                    height) still matter, so treat the result as a
                    <strong>high‑quality starting point</strong>, not a
                    prescription.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-3 py-2 font-medium flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span
                      >Should I size up or down if I’m between two sizes?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-xs">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 hidden faq-answer">
                    Use your flexibility and goals as a guide:
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mt-1">
                      <li>
                        <strong>Choose smaller</strong> if you want a more
                        upright, playful bike or have shorter arms/torso.
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <strong>Choose larger</strong> if you want a stretched,
                        stable position and are flexible.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                    Our result box highlights which side (smaller or larger) we
                    recommend for your selected riding style.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-3 py-2 font-medium flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span
                      >Why does my current bike size feel different from the
                      calculator’s suggestion?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-xs">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 hidden faq-answer">
                    Two bikes with the same “size” label can have very different
                    <strong>reach, stack and seat tube angles</strong>. That’s
                    why a 54 cm in one brand can feel like a 52 or 56 in
                    another. Use our size as a guide, then compare the geometry
                    charts (especially reach and stack) to your current bike
                    that you know feels good or bad.
                  </div>
                </div>

                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full text-left px-3 py-2 font-medium flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span
                      >Can I use this calculator for women’s specific
                      bikes?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-xs">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 hidden faq-answer">
                    Yes. Modern “women’s” bikes are often just regular frames
                    with different contact points (saddle, bars, cranks). The
                    underlying geometry is usually similar, so the same sizing
                    rules apply. If you have relatively longer legs and a
                    shorter torso, you may prefer the
                    <strong>smaller of two suggested sizes</strong> or a shorter
                    stem.
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
